Without Kafka (Synchronous REST calls between independent microservices)

The Order Service directly calls every other service.

                  Customer
                      |
               POST /orders
                      |
                Order Service
       ┌─────────┼──────────┬───────────┐
       │         │          │           │
 Payment API Inventory API Email API Shipping API
       │         │          │           │

Spring boot Example :::

@RestController
@RequestMapping("/orders")
public class OrderController {

    @Autowired
    private PaymentClient paymentClient;

    @Autowired
    private InventoryClient inventoryClient;

    @Autowired
    private EmailClient emailClient;

    @PostMapping
    public String placeOrder(OrderRequest request) {

        paymentClient.pay(request);

        inventoryClient.reserve(request);

        emailClient.sendConfirmation(request);

        return "Order placed";
    }
}

Problem 1 — Slow Response

Suppose:

Service	Response Time
Payment	2 sec
Inventory	3 sec
Email	2 sec
Shipping	4 sec

Total time:

2 + 3 + 2 + 4 = 11 seconds

Customer waits 11 seconds before seeing "Order Placed".

Imagine millions of users experiencing that delay.

Problem 2 — One Failure Breaks Everything

Suppose the Email Service is down.

Order Service
      |
 Email Service ❌

What should happen?

The customer has already:

Paid
Inventory reserved

Should the entire order fail because an email couldn't be sent?

Of course not.

Yet with tightly coupled synchronous calls, that's exactly what can happen if not designed carefully.

Production Problem 3 — Tight Coupling

Order Service knows about:

Payment Service
Inventory Service
Email Service
Shipping Service
Analytics Service
Fraud Service

Every time a new service is introduced, Order Service must change.

That's tight coupling.

Production Problem 4 — Scaling

Black Friday.

Traffic increases 20x.

Email Service becomes overloaded.

Question:

Should Payment Service also scale?

No.

But with poor architecture, one bottleneck can ripple through the system.

Production Problem 5 — Retry Hell

Inventory Service is temporarily unavailable.

Order Service retries.

Payment waits.

Customer waits.

Timeout occurs.

Eventually:

HTTP 500

Customer clicks Place Order again.

Now you may have:

Two payments
Two orders
Duplicate inventory reservations

This is a classic distributed systems problem.


Spring Boot Perspective

The producer becomes very simple.

@Service
public class OrderService {

    @Autowired
    private KafkaTemplate<String, String> kafkaTemplate;

    public void placeOrder(String orderJson) {

        // Save order to database (simplified)

        kafkaTemplate.send("order-topic", orderJson);

        System.out.println("Order event published");
    }
}

Notice:

No call to:

Payment Service
Inventory Service
Email Service
Shipping Service

The Order Service's responsibility is only to create the order and publish the event.

What Happens Next?

Payment Service listens independently.

@KafkaListener(topics = "order-topic")
public void processPayment(String message) {

    System.out.println("Processing payment...");

}

Inventory Service also listens.

@KafkaListener(topics = "order-topic")
public void reserveInventory(String message) {

    System.out.println("Reserving inventory...");

}

Notification Service listens too.

@KafkaListener(topics = "order-topic")
public void sendEmail(String message) {

    System.out.println("Sending confirmation email...");

}

Each service works independently.
